entry.sense:
Sal-aAqN, applied to a speaker, an orator, or a preacher, (JK, IDrd, O, Ḳ,) is like sal-aAqN, (JK,) [i. e.] Eloquent; 
as also miSolaqN↓ [like misolaqN], (IDrd, O, Ḳ) 
and miSolaAqN↓ [like misolaAqN]. (O, Ḳ.)

OaSolamu A man (Ṣ) having his ears (Ṣ, Mgh) or ear (Mṣb) extirpated [by amputation]: (Ṣ, Mgh, Mṣb:) or a slave whose ear has been cut off; 
as also muSal-amN↓: (M:) or a man who is by nature as though his ears had been cut off; 
and so muS-l-amu↓ AlOucunayoni: (Ḳ:) or this last is applied to a man as meaning whose ears have been extirpated by amputation; and to an ostrich as meaning that is naturally as though his ears had been extirpated; (Ṣ;) or [small and short in the ears; i. e.] 
because of the smallness and shortness of his ears; (M;) and it is said that when it is applied to a man, [or rather when a man is likened to an ostrich thus termed,] 
it means his being contemptible, or despised. (TA.) OucunN SalomaMCu means An ear that cleaves to its lobe, or lobule. (M.) 
And AlOaSolamu is an appellation applied to The flea. (Ḳ.)

Sam-aAnN 
Hard ground, (M,) [i. e.] any such ground, (Ḳ,) containing stones, by the side of sands; 
as also Sam-aAnapN↓: (M, Ḳ:) or the latter is a n. un.; and the former signifies hard ground: (Ḥam p. 285:) or rugged ground, (Ṣ, M,) falling short of what is called jabalN: (M:) it is so called because of its hardness. (TA.)

